Here’s the skinny on parsley:

🌱 It’s a cool season herb, so it’s showing off big time in Houston gardens right now.

🌱 parsley is a biennial - which means it can last a couple years in Houston! 

🌱 parsley can be grown in a raised bed or in a pot (but you need a deep pot - the roots can get surprisingly big!)

🌱 parsley is pretty chill when it comes to sunlight needs - it does great in full sun, but we also see it doing great in gardens that only receive about 4 hours of sunlight.

🌱 parsley is best planted as a transplant - starting from seed is a challenge

🌱 we recommend planting extra for the butterflies -  the swallowtail butterfly loves it - so we like to plant extra for the caterpillars to munch on

🌱 parsley is related to carrots - the leaves of parsley look very similar to carrot tops!

🌱 favorite parsley recipe - google shirazi salad. So. Good.

Wanting to get growing but you’re feeling overwhelmed? Not sure where to start? Worried you’ll jump in and fail?

Hello, herb garden!

Herbs are the most welcoming plants to a new gardener. They take you in. Help introduce you to gardening. Give you the confidence you need to stay curious and keep learning. Herbs are kind and gentle to newbies and can pretty much take care of themselves if you give them sunlight and well-draining soil.

Plus, herbs are one of the most practical and functional plants you can grow. No more spending $4 for 4 sprigs of thyme at the grocery store.

And you can’t beat the convenience of popping outside your back door to grab a handful of basil for a recipe or a few stems of mint for an impromptu cocktail when a friend stops by your house.

We can grow herbs year-round in Houston and so many are perennials or biennials (lasting for years in the garden)!

If you’re ready to start, but are feeling unsure - practice with herbs! Fair warning though - they are the gateway crop 😜 - once you feel confident with herbs it won’t be long and you’ll find yourself growing yourself a salad garden! Then you’ll blink and you’ll be growing all 👏🏼 the 👏🏼 things!!

Bad news: basil isn’t a fan of the cold, so it’s time to harvest the basil in your garden!

Good news: basil pesto is super simple to make, and you can freeze it to use throughout the winter! 

Bonus: this pesto is vegan!

Recipe:

2 cups tightly packed basil
1/2 cup walnuts or pine nuts
2 garlic cloves
1/2 cup extra-virgin olive oil
3 tablespoons nutritional yeast
3 tablespoon fresh lemon juice
1 large pinch of sea salt and freshly ground pepper

Toast the pine nuts in a skillet (watch them closely - stirring constantly).

Add all ingredients to a high-speed blender. Blend until smooth.

Serve immediately or freeze in a silicon mold in cubes. Once frozen, pop the cubes out and store in a container in the freezer to use for quick meals during the winter.

To heat up frozen pesto cubes: place cube in a Pyrex cup. Microwave for 1 min. Easy!

It’s about to get really really cold in Houston! 

While our cool weather plants thrive in cool temps- freezing weather? Not so much. We are busy getting our gardens ready for the cold! 

Find a link to the products in the video listed in our stories! You can get everything from Amazon or your favorite local hardware store!

Clients: I’m doing a mental run-through of all your gardens, and I can’t think of a single garden where the products in the video won’t work. They are the perfect width for beds that are 3-4’ wide and are the exact size you need for the obelisks.

Freeze tips:

❄️ water your garden the morning before it freezes, then turn off your sprinkler system to your garden - you don’t want it watering while it’s freezing.

❄️ cover your beds with frost cloths in the late afternoon or early evening before it’s expected to freeze to trap in the warm-ish air. 

❄️ most important: really secure the frost cloth at the soil level with garden stakes or clips.  Use way more than you think you need! Go crazy. Get that garden tucked in! You don’t want any cold air coming in under the cloth.  Even after I use the drawstring at the base of the obelisk covers, I’ll secure the cloth into the soil with the garden stakes. When in doubt - use more garden stakes! 😜

❄️ uncover your plants as soon as the sun is up, and it’s not freezing

Many thanks to @mangiagardens for helping film this for you guys! I wasn’t expecting it to be freezing cold AND raining, so she was such a trooper to show up - because she knows so many of our clients need this info! 

I know I sound like a broken record, but we truly have the best staff ever!

Blueberries are so delicious right now! This kale blueberry smoothie is nutrient dense and yummy.

Recipe:

1/2 frozen banana (if you don’t have frozen, simply add a few pieces of ice before blending).

1-2 cups fresh greens (spinach, kale, swiss chard all work great)

1/2 cup fresh blueberries

1 scoop vanilla protein powder

1 tablespoon ground flax seed (don’t get me started on flax seed - it’s high in fiber, a hormone regulator, helps lower cholesterol AND blood pressure, and the fat in flax seeds helps with absorption of the kale/greens: hello super food!)

1/2 teaspoon cinnamon 

After adding the ingredients to a high-speed blender, cover half-way with water.

Blend until smooth. If you like your smoothies really cold, you might want to add ice before blending.

Yay for starting your day with garden goodness, antioxidants, fiber, and protein!

I’m LOVING this Whoville’s Spiced Up Christmas Margarita from @halfbakedharvest this holiday season.

You can head over to @halfbakedharvest for the recipe (I’ll link to it in our IG stories), but here’s how I’ve been making this gorgeous sugared rosemary to top all the holiday cocktails:

Mix 1/2 cup of water and 1 1/2 cups of sugar on the stove until the sugar is completely melted. Remove from heat. Add a few sprigs of rosemary at a time to completely coat. Cool on a baking rack for at least an hour. Roll in sugar. Separate the leaves of the rosemary a little.

Congrats! You just made such a beautiful garnish for any holiday drink!

When the clock strikes midnight on NYE, I’ll be popping sugared rosemary stems into our champagne! Instant, effortless way to fancy-up a drink!

Bonus: the sugar mixture you dipped your rosemary in - taste it. It’s rosemary simple sugar - so yum! Save it and use it any cocktails. 

The sugared rosemary can be stored a couple days in the refrigerator.

Hello, 2023! We’re so happy to see you!

After an unusually early freeze, several of us lost plants in our gardens. Even plants that usually weather a freeze without issue, did not survive the freeze.

Here’s why:

“Cold tolerance depends on preconditioning. For instance, if broccoli has been growing in warm conditions and temperatures drop below 22 degrees F., it will probably be killed. If these same broccoli plants had experienced cool weather, they would probably survive the sudden cold.” — Texas A&M Agrilife Extension.

If living in Houston has taught us anything, it’s how to roll with the punches, how to regroup, rebuild, and start over.

We’re using this chance to amend our beds heavily with compost and organic fertilizer. We’ll be filling the empty spots in our gardens with cold-hearty plants like kale, lots of spinach, and more root vegetables.

Have you ever spent your holiday with 5 caterpillars? Things get interesting!

Watching this process inside while it was freezing outside was the sweetest holiday gift.

Things we learned:

🐛 Caterpillars eat A LOT. And they grow FAST. It’s unbelievable!

🐛 A caterpillar turns into a chrysalis in a matter of minutes!

🐛 A giant butterfly can somehow fold itself into the size of a peanut. 

🐛 Even the people in your house who you think will be like “meh” about this process will be captivated! 

We brought in a giant bouquet of milkweed, placed it in a vase, and our caterpillars munched it up until they each made a chrysalis.

Thankfully Houston warmed up, and we have been able to take the butterflies back to the garden when they emerge.

If your kale and parsley survived the freeze, this Greek tortellini salad is a great way to eat out of your garden this month. 

Bonus: you can easily make this meal 100% plant based with plant based tortellini and plant based feta.

ASSEMBLE THE FOLLOWING IN A LARGE BOWL:

2 cups chopped kale
2 cups greens (I used arugula)
1 medium cucumber, diced
1 pint halved cherry tomatoes 
1 red bell pepper, diced
15 oz. chopped artichoke hearts
1/2 cup pitted Kalamata olives 
1/2 cup fresh parsley or cilantro 
1/2 cup feta cheese (you can use a vegan brand)
18-20 oz tortellini, cooked (Kite Hill’s vegan option is delicious)

GARDEN DRESSING (good on so many salads)

Place the following in a high speed blender and mix until smooth:

1 cup parsley
1 cup basil
1/4 tsp dried oregano or a couple sprigs of fresh oregano
2 cloves garlic
1/4 cup red wine vinegar
3/4 cup olive oil
1 tsp salt
1/2 tsp black pepper
1 1/2 tsp agave or honey 

Assemble your salad, toss with dressing, enjoy!

Did you know sugar snap peas are considered one of the world’s oldest vegetables? Cool, right?

Sugar snap peas thrive in Houston’s cool season. Since they are considered frost-tolerant, they are great to plant in January. 

🌱 soaking seeds in water for 8-12 hours helps speed up the germination stage 

🌱 plant in a sunny spot - they need at least 8 hours of sun daily

🌱 plant 1” deep and 2” apart

🌱 water well for 10 days

🌱 you can see a seedling pop up within 5 days - but it can take closer to 10 days (remember, water well every day!).

🌱 Check to see if the variety you’re planting is a climbing variety (most that do well in Texas are climbers). If so, you’ll need some vertical growing space.

🌱 expect to harvest in about 2 months

Sugar snap peas are one of my favorite plants to grow in the garden because no cooking is required (can I get a hallelujah?). Dipped in hummus, they are a yummy raw snack straight out of the garden!

Happy pea planting!!

Have you tried growing radishes? They are so easy to grow in Houston, and if you like instant gratification, this might be your new favorite veggie to grow!

🌱 Plant during the cool season in Houston

🌱 Our favorite variety: French Breakfast. They are long and thin, so you can really pack in the plants.

🌱 Plant 1/2” deep and 1” apart. If planting in rows, technically you’re supposed to plant the rows 12” apart, so of course we plant them 6” apart 😜. Have you heard? We’ve kind of got a thing for intensive planting 😍, and we don’t always follow the rules around here 🤭.

🌱 You can see plants pop up in as little as 3-5 days. What?!?

🌱 Even better news? You can harvest in 30 days.

🌱 Water by hand 7 days after planting. 

🌱 Plant new seeds every couple weeks to keep a constant supply of radishes to harvest!

Have you tried a garden and failed?  You're not alone.

So many of us have a similar gardening journey - especially if you live in Houston.

We started off with a whole lot of failure before we learned how to succeed in the garden.

If you've failed at gardening in the past, hear us say:  it's not you.

Gardening in Houston is incredible.  We can grow year-round.  However, it can be challenging.

Our soil stinks.  Our weather?  Don't get a Houstonian started about the weather.

Droughts plus torential floods, scorching summers and unexpected freezes - all in one city in one year.

This is why having the right setup is 80% of the battle. 

Raised beds:  growing in raised beds reduces pest pressure, helps with drainage (plants hate soggy roots), and helps regulate the temperature of the soil.

Gravel:  who wants to walk on muddy grass to spend time in their garden?  Gravel is not only beautiful and keeps your garden area dry year-round, it helps drain the water away from the roots of your plants.

Wide pathways:  if you are comfortable in your garden - guess what:  you like being in your garden!  Our designs think through everything - including how wide pathways need to be to not only feel comfortable but to be functional for wheelbarrow access and maintenance.

Trellises:  Proper trellising matters if you want a great harvest.

Planting plan:  through a whole lot of trial and error and years of experimenting, we've perfected what you can grow every month in Houston.

Education:  we offer monthly videos for our clients and monthly events for our clients and their friends so you can continue to learn and grow in the garden

Maintenance:  want a garden, but want to skip the hassle of caring for a garden?  We offer weekly, bi-weekly, monthly, and quarterly maintenance options.
